And that's a wrap for me folks. So much has changed with the @wildandscenicfilmfestival over the years and I'm happy to have witnessed it in person. My first time at the festival, there were maybe 3 films that shared stories from underrepresented communities and filmmakers of color were sparse at best. This year there were at least 15 films that shared amazing stories of people of color fighting for the environment and simply loving on nature. Filmmakers and producers of color were abundant, which included my friends Graciela and Faith.That is progress! 

Thank you Wild n Scenic for having me as a juror and all that you do to bring attention to the urgent matters around environmental protection.

Whoa.  Point Reyes weather later this week is no joke. SNOW, is possible.
The forecast is for much colder temperatures through late week with snow levels dropping to perhaps 500' . A robust winter storm will begin to impact the entire region on Tuesday as a long-wave trough drops out of western Canada. Wind gusts from Tuesday afternoon into early Wednesday morning are forecast to peak between 45-55 mph with a Wind Advisory in effect for the entire region. The cold air mass will persist over the region through late week with snow levels dropping to around 1,500 to 2,000 feet and at times locally down to 1,000 feet. At this time, 1000MB-500MB thicknesses drop to around 525 dam with 850MB temperatures dropping to as low as -5 deg C which supports the potential for snow flakes mixing down into valley locations, especially during the early morning hours as surface temperatures will hover near freezing.

Monopoly wasn't invented by the Parker Brothers, nor the man they gave it credit for. In 1904, Monopoly was originally called The Landlord's Game, and was invented by a radical woman. Elizabeth Magie's original game had not one, but two sets of rules to choose from.
One was called "Prosperity", where every player won money anytime another gained a property. And the game was won by everyone playing only when the person with the least doubled their resources. A game of collaboration and social good.
The second set of rules was called "Monopoly", where players succeeded by taking properties and rent from those with less luck rolling the dice. The winner was the person who used their power to eliminate everyone else.
Magie's mission was to teach us how different we feel when playing Prosperity vs Monopoly, hoping that it would one day change national policies. 
When the Parker Bros adopted the game, they erased Magie, they erased the "Prosperity" rules and celebrated "Monopoly". This is why very few games of Monopoly end in better friendships! Some even end friendships! What they couldn't erase was Magie's lesson.

@outdoorresearch has a pretty cool, PAID internship opportunity.
( Check out their website for more details )

Outdoor Research is looking to build diversity in the outdoor industry by offering 5 underrepresented students the opportunity to intern within one of our ten departments for 6 weeks. Interns will have the opportunity to work on projects that build their skillset, learn cross functional dynamics and building connections within the outdoor industry along with fellow interns. You’ll have the opportunity to present your final project to the Executive Team.

What would qualify as underrepresented in the outdoor industry? Cultural or Identity

Which departments are you interested in learning more about?

Direct to Consumer - The e-commerce team combines technology, user experience, analytics, merchandising and digital marketing to develop a direct relationship with our customers.

Marketing OR – Attracting new customers in our established OR outdoor apparel line (building on current momentum in the outdoor industry)

Materials – Selecting the appropriate materials for the needed garment, balancing many variables in the process – breathability, waterproofness, durability, availability, sustainability and price, etc.

Product Design – Designing future styles based on market analysis and consumer needs

Sales – Wholesale or OR Pro - Working with our various sales representatives, distributors and specialty retailers (ski shops, REI, outdoor stores, etc.) across the country / globe to align order fulfillment and provide top class service.

Supply Chain- Ensure that the right amount of product is available to the customer at the right place and the right time (Forecasting customer demand, executing procurement plan, monitoring production, coordinating delivery from factories to fulfillment centers)

Anticipated Internship Dates: June 20 – July 28

Located in Seattle, interns would need to be in-house at least 3 days per week dependent on the department.

For all the fierce kick-ass women who have had others try to define them. 

She walked to the forest and sat with the 
trees. She heard the wind whisper and dance with the leaves. And she spoke to the willow, the elm and the 
pine. And she told them what she’d been told time after time.

She told them she felt she was never enough,
she was either too little or far, far too much.
Too loud or too quiet, too fierce or too weak,too wise or too foolish, too bold or too meek.

Then she found a small clearing surrounded by
firs and she stopped and she heard what the trees said to her, and she sat there for hours not wanting to leave, for the forest said nothing, it just let her breathe.

So on point, Christopher Riddick:

"If you thought Caitlin Clark’s “you can’t see me” hand gesture was pretty cool last week but Angel Reese making the same gesture was classless today, then you must be honest about what’s driving your reactions.

If you’re saying “well Reese made the gesture towards Clark” while seeming not to know that Clark made her gesture towards Louisville’s Hailey Van Lith, then you must examine why you fixated on the details of one event and cared less about the details of the other. 

Some folks get to be “confident” while others are called “arrogant.”

Some folks are called “passionate” while others are labeled “angry.”

Some folks are praised for “exhibiting leadership qualities” while others are chastised for “not knowing their place.”

Some folks are called “go getters” while others are supposedly “overly aggressive.”

When we encourage certain behaviors for particular social identities while criticizing others for demonstrating those same behaviors we perpetuate work environments that are not inclusive, that damage psychological safety, and stand in the way of authenticity and belongingness."

Engaged in this conversation with a well meaning individual and I walked away with this question. What say you?

A few years ago, Intro Limited got hired to find a particular type of VP for a lifestyle brand. To kick off the search, the brand gave us a list of 90 people from their previous recruiter. “We hated all of these people. Bring us better candidates.”

I thought wow, the previous recruiter presented 90 people?! All of them straight rejected? And now it's our turn? Intimidating ask, but we dug in.

On that long list, I saw many familiar names, but one stuck out. We’ll call her Annie. I phoned the company. “Why didn’t you like Annie?”

“We never talked to her. We just dismissed her profile because we don’t like the brand she comes from.”

I gave them 10 unexpected reasons why Annie was likely the right person for their VP role.

“OK, we’ll take a second look at Annie. Set up an interview. But meanwhile, show us more people.”

We showed them 40 more people. They interviewed and deliberated. For 4 months.

Then they hired Annie.

What was the difference between us presenting Annie, vs. the other recruiter presenting her? I came to find out that the other recruiter didn’t really KNOW most of the 90 people that they had shown. Their “presentation” was basically a database download.

We had known Annie for 6 years. With the personal and professional context that we provided, Annie was a completely different candidate.

It’s been almost 3 years and Annie is still at that company, exceeding expectations.

But this is not a story about recruiting, it’s about relationship building. A lot of people believe that merit should stand on its own, but let me tell you: the higher the stakes, the more important relationships are.
